#NewPaper from Liboiron et al addresses how much & what kinds of plastic pollution exist in #Greenland & Tasiujarjuaq, Nunavut. #LoveYourDataWeek can now be EVERY week - recordings and slide decks are now available for most talks on the UC Love Data Week 2021 website. Check out the talks on publishing #data, APIs, #GIS data, tidy data, and more! https://t.co/Tmqko4PwIJ #TidyTuesday https://t.co/ZnxIHGEJcp

#NewPaper from Culberg et al cites SIX datasets from the Arctic Data Center! Read "Extreme melt season ice layers reduce firn permeability across Greenland" and explore all the cited data: https://t.co/MQRUWNtD9P #OpenAccess #SynthesisScience #DataReuse https://t.co/5z2VooSoGo
What a beautiful chart! Data for this can be found at the @arcticdatactr: https://t.co/GgU8tcJlOT #dataviz https://t.co/o2spddnVu0

#SaveTheDate October 5-7 for a great #conference opportunity - Citizen Science in the Far North - that'll focus on sharing best practices and challenges of conducting citizen science research in the Arctic. More info from @ArcticResearch: https://t.co/sBgk3JeoaN https://t.co/taxLoDKHTJ

New resource: an #ArcGIS StoryMap from @MOSAiCArctic! The Central #Arctic may look like a barren ice-covered seascape, but it is home to a rich #ecosystem - scroll through this resource to learn more about how all the pieces are interconnected. #education https://t.co/PDm6aeDssg https://t.co/pibdcIQ1qX

#NewPaper: "Climate Drivers of Arctic Tundra Variability and Change using an Indicators Framework" from Uma Bhatt & colleagues! Read it here https://t.co/aIvIqIWI42 & check out some time series #tundra data from Bhatt at the Arctic Data Center: https://t.co/JcRM6xYBcF #OpenAccess https://t.co/MQzScIzIpw

Do political views correlate with knowledge of the #Arctic? Hamilton et al. explore two kinds of polar knowledge in a cool new paper stressing the importance of outreach and communication in #polar #research. https://t.co/AFenLIzmGm https://t.co/GCQc9Z7lcL
We'll be there, and you should be too! Sounds like a great talk about #Indigenous #Technology and #Inuit History. https://t.co/yTf24UIy4w

@uafairbanks is hosting a fun event showcasing #Arctic research: Flash Talks! These short, snappy presentations by scientists & students feature new research in climate sci, geoscience, fisheries, social sci, & more. Register & tune in on 20 May 5-7 pm PT: https://t.co/HcoiTOLs4p https://t.co/y1AnwhIka4

Also in this session is John Woitkowitz - a historian talking about the #cartography and legacies of 19th century #Arctic science. There's a long and complicated tradition of mapping in the Arctic from Indigenous paths to Mercator in the 1500s. https://t.co/oyZMeRK7ne

Presented early but the recording will be made available! Spoke about the #data portals service, which makes it easy for researchers to collect relevant #datasets all in one place. Check out more info and get started building your own #portal today! https://t.co/DLH6rEsHuF https://t.co/L22JTSIdui
Final session of the @Polar_Research conference! We'll be presenting at 2:05 pm Pacific time on our data portals service for #Arctic and #polar researchers.

Next: Liz Weinberg & others from @IARPCCollab discussing the Future of US Federally Funded #Arctic Research - and the early career forum that enables ECRs to network, find collaborate, share research, and impact the next Arctic Research Plan! https://t.co/HQrbeRq1HG https://t.co/Or7UNACJjK

Next: Ekaterina Sharova from the Arctic Art Institute - their project is the first one to work to understand the historical culture of northern Russian peasants and trying to protect the embroidery and textile production. https://t.co/ofxYeAl24F

This Significance of Ice-loss to Landscapes in the #Arctic (SILA) project is another one that has an #instagram! Follow them there for images from their work: https://t.co/1V6vns99EE https://t.co/X36kiCVuvE

Next: @quincy_faber discussing a new @NSF interdisciplinary project that's tackling ice loss in #Arctic #Greenland. Two goals: the science, but also #communication around the science. Loving how many of these talks feature #scicomm as part of the project rather than an "add on". https://t.co/YCGl1lniim

He also started a #scicomm Instagram account to bring more awareness to these #glaciers in Colombia (seeing as most think of it as a tropical country!) - check it out here! https://t.co/AQwHlCUdoH https://t.co/5uhLHpyfjj

We're back for the 5th session of @Polar_Research! Sebastian Barbosa is discussing his geological mapping work on paleo-tropical #glaciers via Google Earth - a super accessible tool to get to the remote glacial areas of #Colombia even during COVID-19. https://t.co/KYZZ11pvDt

Next: Deborah Bozzato speaking about "smelly molecules" (dimethylsulfate or DMS) and phytoplankton that she studied as part of @MOSAiCArctic. This molecule is a defense mechanism for phytoplankton, a chemical cue, and an effector on the climate. https://t.co/hhY63COoIu

Next up: Nuno Pereira talking about his #Antarctica Induced Music project, in which students (his sons as guinea pigs!) chose 10 out of 50 photos of Antarctica, said why, and then set those photos to #music. Next steps are to bring this project to more students! #scicomm #STEAM
Her reason for this work? "Not many people can speak in the scientific way, but everyone can understand the message of visual arts." #scicomm

At the APECS International Virtual Conference today: Anastasia Deyko is discussing her new "Arctic instagram" Appearing of Disappearing, where people can contribute their pictures of the #Arctic so that we can have a map of comparable photos from the 20th century and beyond. https://t.co/X45r6m7Yjz

With #ClimateChange happening faster in the #Arctic, coasts there are eroding faster than other places. Until now there hasn't been a numerical model that projects #erosion rates - enter Rolph et al and their model ArcticBeach 1.0! Read more: https://t.co/c6a4Viu9YI https://t.co/NpOW9jd0zq

This #NewPaper - Temporary pause in the growth of atmospheric #ethane & #propane in 2015-2018 (https://t.co/AJVcwM0KFs) from @HeleneAngot et al - uses two datasets from the Arctic Data Center! https://t.co/ntArYhZS30 & https://t.co/nOCk63p2uU. #AtmosphericScience #Hydrocarbons https://t.co/sf65kgM61v

Freshwater input to the #Arctic has increased in the past 30 years & associated with intense #warming of air temps & decreases in #seaice extent. Read work from Alexander Shiklomanov here https://t.co/EB1JtOqmfw & look at some of his river data here https://t.co/JsFjBmZBfP. https://t.co/xiK3ERPqB6

The Arctic Data Center makes sure it's easy to #cite #data within your paper - all submitted datasets get a DOI! Plus, if that #DOI isn't in your original paper, you can link your article to your data after the fact within our repository. More here: https://t.co/GQTk8asP1L https://t.co/INknMzFa3a

A wise perspective: "the #Arctic is often portrayed in a simplified...way...[this] limits a deeper understanding of the issues that are important to the people living there." Read more about how we imagine the Arctic & how to challenge that view: https://t.co/jiHL9FMb9P https://t.co/ywYqdPWW0N
